A Two-Step Structural Model for the Collatz Contraction

Author: Amir Mohammad Shiravani (Raein)

Abstract

This paper explores the intrinsic structure of the Collatz transformation through a focused analysis of its two-step odd-even composite cycle. By defining Ts(n) = (3n + 1)/2 for odd n, the study examines the net growth factor (3/2 + 1/(2n)) and demonstrates how this formulation imposes a theoretical contraction trend on the overall system. Numerical simulations for n ≤ 10s confirm the average contraction behavior, supporting the heuristic argument for convergence in the Collatz map.

1. The Two-Step Odd–Even Transformation

The Collatz map T(n) = 3n + 1 transforms any odd integer into an even number, which is immediately halved in the following step. Combining these two operations yields the two-step map Ts(n) = (3n + 1)/2. The net growth factor is thus given by:

Ts(n)/n = (3n + 1)/(2n) = 3/2 + 1/(2n) For large n, this ratio approaches 1.5, implying that each odd-even cycle increases n by roughly 50%. Since subsequent divisions in even runs dominate this expansion, the long-term dynamic of the sequence is globally contracting.

